<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98314059724459></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98314059724459><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98314059724459>RE: Melee or Mediate</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98314059724459#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=492><span id=Sage>Gorthin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>149 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Feb 25th 5:36 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>"If we can get Gorthin to ever post again he could give you a detailed account of how he did it. He is one of the most articulate posters on The Life of a Shaman that I have read in any board. He's good."<br><br>*blush*<br> Warning: this is long.....<br><br>Well, I have been quiet the last few days as most people have been, IMO, adequately answering various questions that come up.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also, due to some RL issues, which I will not bore anyone here with, I have been busy with other things.<br><br>As to how to get and keep defense/AC as high as possible, here is what I have found.<br><br>Equipment:  It goes without saing that high base AC equipment= higher AC overall.  I know it seems simple, but many overlook it.  How many of you Shamen out there will sacrifice 3 points of raw AC for 5 points of strength?  Some will, some won't.  Those 5 points of strength do not do &gt;jack&lt; for a Shaman.  For a tank, possibly.  Let me illustrate.<br><br>Shaman.  One swing per 3 seconds with a Jade prod.  Let us say it takes 10 strength to get 1 damage point (as most tank boards claim).  So you give up 6 raw AC for 10 strength.  Ok.  So, in that 9 second time frame, where you will get three swings, you will have a potential of &gt;3&lt; extra damage.  Is this worth giving up 10 net AC? I hope most of you figure out the correct answer =)<br><br>Tank.  Dual wielding.  Gets the strength bonus off hand (not 1h weapon bonus).  Delay of 22 on both weapons.  So primary will swing 4 times in 9 seconds &gt;guaranteed&lt;.  Let's say he double attacks twice.  6 attacks primary.  4 potential swings off hand.  Dual wields twice, double attacks once off hand.  Three swings off hand.  That is a potential 9 damage in the same time frame.  Will they remove AC for that strength bonus?  The smart tank WON'T.  He will get a Strength buff from us or (gag) a Druid or Enchanter (smirk).<br><br>Shaman 3, Tank 9.<br><br>Now, consider the shaman will generally not be meleeing the whole fight.  That "benefits" of his damage bonus become more and more questionable.  The same goes for other stats.  The ONLY stat I will give up AC for is Wisdom, and if you read the next part, you will see I am not very willing to do that.<br><br>Armor class, however, is ALWAYS of use.  Unless, that is, you have an relatively rare group where the tank always has taunt under control, and you never get aggroed on slowing or healing, or root parking.  And in the 50+ game, taunt doesn't work nearly as well as before.  Once you see those lovely "You will not evade me Gorthin", be prepared to take some lovin.<br><br>Wisdom vs AC, the great debate:  Ah yes.  Once camp screams "200 Wisdom!!!!".  The other "max AC!".  Which is right?  Neither, but lean towards the AC.  You &gt;have&lt; to find a balance. Once you hit about level 40, you primary goal should be to hit 800 AC.  If your defense skill is current, you should be able to tell about how close to 800 you are.  If going down to 165 wisdom will get you to 800 AC, DO IT.  Even if it is 801 AC, with you being fully self buffed, just make sure you hit 801.  Some of the banned programs have shown that 800 AC is a magical spot.  When you hit it, damage taken drops dramatically.  And I believe this, too.  At 780 AC, Drolvargs in Dreadlands were hitting me for near max, almost all the time the connected.  Once I went to 800+ AC, that &gt;stopped&lt;.  My average damage went to about 60% of their max.  That is a HUGE difference.  900 ac is the next goal, but that takes some high end gear....<br><br>But why would you give up Wisdom?  Let me ask you this.  How often, in a well balanced group THAT STAYS BUSY, do you hit full mana?  Personally, I &gt;never&lt; do.  I am either buffing, debuffing, healing, chloroplasting, nuking, Doting, invising, sowing etc etc &gt;someone&lt; in the group or a monster.  Do you know how muc Mana you get from 10 wisdom at level 30?  60 mana.  Ooooooo.  Hey, that's an extra SoW if you med to full.  Wheeeeeeeee.  Yes, more wis = less fizzles, but most of us do not fizzle &gt;that&lt; much.  Don't make the mistake of thinking Wisdom is the be all end all of the Shaman (or any other wisdom based caster) class.  Yes, more Wisdom is a good thing (tm), but it is not going to be the end of the world if you only manage to "scrape" up 160 wisdom.  <br><br>Just for the record, Gorthin has (last time I looked, Monk addiction) 840ish AC self buffed with a 176 Wisdom.  In a normal group with no overpulls (where everyone goes OOM), I never have problems with mana, either way aka too much or too little.  I tend to float around 40m most of the time cycling buffs and slows.  But I am MUCH more capable now that I can root park, aggro heal, and even emergency tank (yes, even at 51).  That is because of my Armor class, not wisdom.<br><br>Defense:  Man this skill sucks.  There is no trick to getting this to stay current.  Until I hit about 185 in the defense skill, soloing the first bubble or two of a new level was enough to max it out.  But once 185 hits *scream*.  I went three complete levels without a single improve at one point.  Here are some tips:<br><br>Buff agi, dex, str, and stamina.  Noone knows for sure which skills affect Defense to what degree, but hey, we are buffing masters, use it.<br><br>Solo tank mobs.  Slow, Dot, and melee the mobs to death.  You can do this all the way from level 5 when you get your first slow spell.  At 51, I can still do this without a problem.  Ice giants feel my wrath on a semi-regular basis when I need some <br>"phat lewtz".  I know slowing the mob removes some chances of it increasing, but without a good dodge cap, and no parry/block or ripotse, we are dead meat at higher levels.<br><br>Once you hit about 195, just let the improves come on their own.  It is not worth the frustration to try to specifically improve the skill.  Just root park, take a minor beating on Slow and heals, and you will get those final points.  197 to 200 was from root parking in Karnor's for me.  I didn't even know it was going up until I saw You have become better at defense (200)! during one root park.  Needless to say, I was quite happy.<br><br>Hope that tirade at least helps someone.  I got the lack of posting recently out of my system =P<br><br>Gorthin Spiritcaller<br>51 Shaman BB<br>Drindal<br>43 Monk BB<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
