<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98328219352751></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98328219352751><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98328219352751>RE: Melee or Mediate</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98328219352751#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=492><span id=Sage>Gorthin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>149 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Feb 27th 8:56 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.10]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There is not a strength bonus difference for 1h and 2h weapons.&nbsp;&nbsp;It is all based upon the &gt;delay&lt; of the weapon.<br><br>Basically, fast 2h weapons only have a bonus very similar to 1h weapons.  Once the delay hits 43+, they start getting a very large per hit damage bonus.  This is why Executioner axes (an old standby for warriors) hit so darned hard.  This was to help 2h weapons to have a chance of being used over low damage, fast 1h weapons.  People were just taking advantage of the damage bonus on the 1h fast weapons, so Verant actually did something to try to bring 2h weapons back within a respectable damage range.<br><br>Gorthin Spiritcaller<br>51 Shaman BB<br>Drindal <br>43 Monk BB<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
